<br>
Anyone know the basic principles of Bartering? You offer above what you want and then you have leeway to trim back and still be happy. IF the person your bartering with thinks your high offer is good then you still come out ahead.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Should we actually propose this to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, I want it well thought out, balanced, and with intelligent arguments in its behalf.<br>
<br>
If I propose something that I know to be too good, unbalanced, and then offer arguments in its behalf, I am being dishonest.<br>
<br>
In addition, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> could no doubt benefit from rational, intelligent and honest discussions of what is balanced.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 1 extra charge is good and is not better, NEARLY better is the whole idea...near but not.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Simply adding one charge to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Rod of Modulation</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> as it stands yields a mana to HP ratio of 100/450 = 22.2%.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Rod of Transvergence</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> yields a mana to HP ratio of 220/900 = 24.4%, hardly distinguishable.  On the other hand, raising the cost by 25 mana means the ratio is 75/450 = 16.6%, still a net gain.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> There is a strong reason for adding a watered down version at lower level. T-rod is arguably the single best mage spell there is.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Qualify that by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;non-pet spell&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and I would agree.  They are both harmful AND addictive!<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> So, it is somewhat class defining. And having a class defining spell that late makes little sense. Several other class defining spells have been moved down in levels, for other reason thou<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I basically agree, which is why I made my initial suggestion, however, I see some counter arguments.<br>
<br>
Is it really necessary before 44th level?  This is the beginnings of when raiding becomes possible, and that is really where rods are most useful by design.  Adding another charge to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Modulating Rod</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and increasing the mana cost to 225 would allow it to be used to transfer mana between pools at about the right level for it to be used.<br>
<br>
Is it even <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>possible</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> at a level much lower than 44?  The ability to transfer mana depends on fast, mana efficient healing.  Other than <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Complete Heal</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> at 39, the mana to hitpoint healed ratio is much lower for lower level spells.  So even if a single charge net gain rod existed at 29th or 34th level, it would be of marginal utility.<br>
<br>
On the other had, it would add <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> some</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mana regeneration, storage, and transfer capability, and so might well be worth it.<br>
<br>
Perhaps <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Summon Rod of Tittilation</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, level 34, costs 100 mana, has one charge that yields 125 mana for 150 hit point loss.<br>
<br>
Better than the current <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Modulating Rod</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, just barely useful to transfer or regenerate mana.  Would not likely unbalance raids.<br>
<br>
Those numbers I just pulled out of my hat, and they may be very wrong.<br>
<br>
But it's an idea.<br>
<br>
And you're right, they HAVE been making lower level versions of class defining spells.<br>
<br>
